      • onEnd

        protected void onEnd​(com.idevicesinc.sweetblue.BleTransaction.EndReason reason)
        Called when a transaction ends, either due to the transaction itself finishing itself through fail() or succeed(), or from the library implicitly ending the transaction, for example if getDevice() becomes BleDeviceState.BLE_DISCONNECTED. Override this method to wrap up any loose ends or notify UI or what have you.

      • getAtomicity

        protected com.idevicesinc.sweetblue.BleTransaction.Atomicity getAtomicity()
        Default is Boolean.FALSE. Optionally override if you want your transaction's reads/writes to execute "atomically". This means that if you're connected to multiple devices only the reads/writes of this transaction's device will be executed until this transaction is finished.

      • getDevice

        public RxBleDevice getDevice()
        Returns the device this transaction is running on.

        Returns whether the transaction is currently running.

      • cancel

        public void cancel()

      • fail

        public boolean fail()
        Call this from subclasses to indicate that the transaction has failed. Usually you call this in your GenericListener_Void.onEvent(Event) when ReadWriteListener.Status is something other than ReadWriteListener.Status.SUCCESS. If you do so, DeviceReconnectFilter.ConnectFailEvent.txnFailReason() will be set.
        Returns:
        false if the transaction wasn't running to begin with.

      • succeed

        public boolean succeed()
        Call this from subclasses to indicate that the transaction has succeeded.
        Returns:
        Boolean.FALSE if the transaction wasn't running to begin with.

      • getTime

        public double getTime()
        Returns the total time that this transaction has been running. You can use this in update(double) for example to fail() or succeed() a transaction that has taken longer than a certain amount of time.
        See Also:
        BleTransaction.update(double)
